\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Spike-rate adaptation
\series default
: Lengthening of the interspike intervals over time when a neuron is injected
 with a constant current before it settles into a 
\series bold
steady-state value
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Inclusion of adaptation into the framework of integrate-and-fire models
 is problematic 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Reset mechanism after the spike emission means that the history of the m
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
embrane potential and previous spike times is forgotten 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Renewal behavior facilitates the analytic study, but makes including adaptation
 difficult 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Leaky integrate-and-fire neuron with conductance synapses and adaptation
 current 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{\text{adapt}}(t)=-g_{\text{adapt}}(t)[v(t)-V_{0}]
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\text{adapt}}(t)$
\end_inset

 is a time-dependent shunting conductance 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Shunting refers to synaptic conductance short-circuit currents (short-circuit
 allows current to flow along unintended path with no or very low impedance)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Each output spike increases this conductance by a fixed amount 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\text{inc}}$
\end_inset

 and between spikes the conductance decays exponentially 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{\text{adapt}}(t)\frac{dg_{\text{adapt}}(t)}{dt}=-g_{\text{adapt}}(t)+\sum_{t_{\text{out}}}g_{\text{inc}}\delta(t-t_{\text{out}})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
